ng Sectarian Judaism: The Centrality of the Priesthood in the Second Temple Period -- tPart 4. The Bible and Archaeology -- tIn Defense of Forgery -- tCan Archaeology Serve as a Tool in Textual Criticism of the Hebrew Bible? -- t"You Shall Make for Yourself No Molten Gods": Some Thoughts on Archaeology and Edomite Ethnic Identity -- tFemale Infanticide in Iron II Israel and Judah -- tPart 5. Religion and Religious Studies -- tElements of Popular Piety in Late Medieval and Early Modern Jewish Psalms Commentary -- tThe Biblical Icon -- tWalter Rauschenbusch, the Social Gospel Movement, and How Julius Wellhausen Unwittingly Helped Create American Progressivism in the Twentieth Century -- t"Starving" the Patient: A Jewish Perspective on Terry Schiavo and the Feeding Tube Controversy -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Scripture0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRichard Friedman is well known in the field of biblical studies, not only because of his contributions to the study of the Hebrew Bible (which are many) but also because he has written cogently and clearly for a much wider audience, outside the academy, most notably in his Who Wrote the Bible? (1997). In addition, his influence has crossed the boundaries of a variety of disciplines such as source criticism, archaeology, the ancient Near East, as well as religious studies.The essays in this volume reflect the breadth and depth of Richard Friedman's life and work. Several contributors discuss topics related to the Hebrew Bible: for example, Jacob Milgrom examines the relationship between Ezekiel and the Levites and Carol Meyers discusses the Tabernacle texts in the context of Priestly influence on them; Ronald Hendel, Michael Homan, and Robert Wilson explore the history of source criticism, with detailed source-critical analysis of Genesis 1-11 and the book of Kings. Jeffrey Geoghegan discusses the origins of the Passover in one of several insightful essays under the topic "Israel and the Ancient Near East." Among the contributions specific to archaeology, Baruch Halpern's provides a provocative "Defense of Forgery." Lastly, four contributors (e.g., Alan Cooper) discuss religion and religious studies, along with ramifications for contemporary application. A fine collection of contemporary topics discussed by leading scholars in the field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aCassedy, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDever, William G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDolansky, Shawna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDolansky, Shawna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEmerton, John A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForbes, . Dean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreedman, David Noel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarr, W. Randall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeoghegan, Jeffrey C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalpern, Baruch, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendel, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoman, Michael M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuffmon, Herbert Bardwell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLemaire, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat